	<td>
	  <font size="2" face="Verdana">
		Subject:&nbsp;<b>RE: what pet to use</b></font>
		
		<a href="MB_Editmsg.asp?FID=64&FN=Magician&SID=7&SN=EverQuest&TID=1865147&TN=what+pet+to+youse&CAT=Classes&SURL=http%3A%2F%2Fwww%2Eeverlore%2Ecom&MSID=1997623&PL=4&amp;action=REPLY"><img src="http://www.everlore.com/gimages/btn_reply.gif" border="0" align="right" alt="Reply to message"></a>
		<br>
		<img src="http://www.everlore.com/gimages/Icons/icon1.gif" border="0" align="ABSCENTER" width="15" height="15">
		<font size="2" face="Verdana">
		<font size="1" face="Verdana">posted 7/14/2003 8:10:11 PM&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;

		
		<a href="US_Show.asp?id=133678">
		<img src="http://www.everlore.com/gimages/profile.gif" border="0" alt="Click Here to See the Profile for Witch of Felwithe" width="22" height="11"></a>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
		
		<a href="MSG_MailBox.asp?mode=new&amp;sendto=Witch+of+Felwithe">
		<img src="http://www.everlore.com/gimages/privatemsg.gif" border="0" alt="Click Here to Message Witch of Felwithe" width="22" height="11"></a>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
		
		<a href="MB_editmsg.asp?FID=64&FN=Magician&SID=7&SN=EverQuest&TID=1865147&TN=what+pet+to+youse&CAT=Classes&SURL=http%3A%2F%2Fwww%2Eeverlore%2Ecom&MSID=1997623&PL=4">
		<img src="http://www.everlore.com/gimages/edit.gif" border="0" alt="Edit/Delete Message" width="18" height="13"></a>
		
		</font>
		<hr size="1">Each pet has advantages and drawbacks.  These are my observations of the pre-level 50 (non-epic) pets.  My opinions are, of course, influenced by my personal killing style.  I don't want to have to use my mana healing my pets.  I'm a damage dealer, not a pet cleric.  I'm terrible at chain casting pets.  If I can't kill the mob with one pet, I'm in trouble.  My goal is to kill the mob as quickly as possible.  Your killing style will help determine your pet choices.</P><P>Earth<BR>Advantages:  <BR>Highest HP of all our pets.  This clod can really take a beating.<BR>Frequently casts root.  This allows you to nuke faster and harder without the mob being able to come over and start whacking on your delicate magician noggin.  <BR>Where the mobs are fairly close together it will keep your mob from running for reinforcements when its health gets low.</P><P>Disadvantages:<BR>Very low agility.<BR>Does the least amount of damage of all the pets.  The earth pet often misses when it swings.<BR>Gets hit more often than any other pet due to the low agility.  Keep a DS on this pet at all times.  <BR>A rooted mob will keep swinging at your pet until one of them is dead.<BR>Slow HP regen.<BR>Casts no DD spell.</P><P>When to use to best advantage:</P><P>Solo - When hunting in areas with a lot of aggro mobs fairly close together.<BR>When hunting mobs who dish out more damage than your other pets can survive.</P><P>Grouped - When you need to keep the mobs in one spot.  There are times when this is vital.</P><P>Personal opinion:  While many magicians will put the earth pet at the top of their list for soloing it's my least favorite.  It simply doesn't do as much damage as I like.  Those massive HP also take quite a bit of time to regen.  If I'm in a group where we need to keep the mobs rooted I use it.  Always cast a DS on this pet.</P><P>Fire<BR>Advantages:<BR>Highest DPS of all the pets.<BR>Casts an unresistable damage shield on itself freeing up one of your spell slots.<BR>Casts a fire based DD spell.<BR>The high damage output keeps the aggro on this pet very effectively.<BR>Fair agility.</P><P>Disadvantages:<BR>Have to wait for the pet to cast the damage shield on itself.<BR>The HP is noticably lower than the earth or water pets.<BR>When you're grouped, that sweet DS doesn't come into play unless your pet is the main tank.  The mobs simply won't be aggroed on your pet.</P><P>When to use to best advantage:</P><P>Solo - When hunting in areas where the mobs are fairly well spaced.  The mobs WILL run from this pet and its wicked DS.<BR>Against fast hitting mobs.  They simply cook themselves on this pet.<BR>Against mobs with low fire resistance.</P><P>Group - When the earth pet's root or the air pet's stun isn't needed, unless the mobs you're hunting have high fire resistance.</P><P>Personal opinion:  At lower levels I HATED this pet.  Sure it did great damage, but often died because I couldn't heal it fast enough.  Once I got the lvl 29 fire pet, my opinion changed.  I used this pet almost exclusively through levels 30-46 or so.  Give this pet summoned armor and weapons.  It seemed to make a world of difference.  You may have to heal the pet (usually once per fight).</P><P>Water<BR>Advantages:<BR>Second only to the earth pet in HP.<BR>Fast HP regen.<BR>Immune to poison.<BR>Casts a cold based DD spell.<BR>Respectable DPS.</P><P>Disadvantages:<BR>Not as useful against mobs with high cold resistance.</P><P>When to use to best advantage:<BR>Solo - Whenever you need a well rounded pet.  When fighting against mobs that poison.</P><P>Group - Whenever the air pet's stun and the earth pet's root isn't needed, and the targets don't have high cold resistance.</P><P>Personal opinion:  This is simply a solid pet for soloing.  The combination of decent HP, good agility and fast regen make this an excellent choice at lower levels.  It's  perfect for fighting giant spiders, venomous snakes, etc.  This pet saw a lot of action in my pre level 29 days.  Give this pet summoned armor & weapons, cast your DS on it and go to town.</P><P>Air<BR>Advantages:<BR>Excellent agility, which means this pet simply doesn't get hit much.<BR>Frequently stuns mob, which keeps it from hitting for a few seconds & interrupts casting.  This is the pet of choice when fighting caster mobs.<BR>High damage output.</P><P>Disadvantages:<BR>The least amount of HP of all the pets.<BR>Casts invisiblity on itself.  Either get a "see invis" item or keep that spell handy when hunting with this pet.  This is not a serious drawback.</P><P>Personal opinion:  This pet didn't see much play at lower levels, simply because I wasn't often fighting caster mobs, and it often died quickly due to the low HP.  In the mid forties, this became my pet of choice.  Between the stunning and the high agility, this pet just doesn't take many hits.  If it's getting a bit beat up, give it some summoned armor.</P><P>A couple other things we magicians must learn:<BR>Aggro management, both solo and when grouped.  Let the pet whack your mobs for a few seconds before you nuke.  Space out your nukes to keep your pet on top of the aggro list.  If you find the mobs are ignoring your pet and coming right for you, you're "over nuking".  When grouped, if you do manage to pull aggro, stand still and STOP NUKING.  Let the tank solidly rebuilt aggro on him/herself, then get out of the way.  I've often watched various damage casters in a group continue to nuke while a mob was hitting them.  Meanwhile, the cleric is wasting mana trying to keep the caster alive and the melee classes are trying to regain the mob's attention.  It just makes everyone job harder.<BR>Strive for perfect pet control.  Many people are still hesitant to hunt with a pet class.  Show them how awesome a magician with a well trained pet can be.  Learn to quickly pull your pet off one mob and sick it on another.  When you're in a group without an enchanter, your pet can keep an add occupied until the group is ready to deal with it.</P><P>Whew, this is a bit more than I intended to type.  I hope young magicians find it helpful.</P><P>Yanari, Witch of Felwithe<BR>Merry meet, merry part<BR>and merry meet again.</P><P>Message edited by: Witch of Felwithe (7/14/2003 8:04:50 PM)</P><P>Message edited by: Witch of Felwithe (7/14/2003 8:10:11 PM)<br>&nbsp;<br>&nbsp;<br></font>
	</font>
	</td>
</tr>
